headline.main: Arrival of the Merlin--Sickness on Board the Danish Vessel Enchantress.

docs.lead_paragraph: By the arrival of the Mcrlin at this port from Bermuda, we learn that business is looking up at St. Thomas. The health of the Island is very good-never was more so-weather very hot and close. The steamer Medway, at St. Thomas, left Navy Bay Oct. 9 for Carthagena.

headline.main: FROM ST. THOMAS.; Changes in the Government. Change of Port Regulations--The Fever General News.

docs.lead_paragraph: You will perceive by the accompanying papers, which I send, that quite a change has been effected in the Government of our Island. Cont. V. OxROLM has been dismissed from his office, and retires on a pension of two thousand dollars a year. His dismission was recommended by Gov. HANSEN two years ago, when the home Government was taking measures to reduce the expenses of its Colonial possessions in the West Indies.

headline.main: The Sickness on the Ship Washington.

docs.lead_paragraph: To the Editor of the New-York Daily Times: In your paper of this morning, under the head " Cholera at Quarantine," I find noticed the arrival of the packet ship Washington, with 952 passengers on board, and also that she has had no less than 73 deaths, besides several cases sent to Qu rantine Hospital.

docs.lead_paragraph: To the Editor of the New-York Daily Times: In your paper of Oct. 7, you have certain observations on "Public Scourges; their Origin and Preventives," in which you maintain that quarantine is only a prevention against diseases of foreign origin, when the city quarantined abounds in filth and putrescence; that is the penalty for defective street and health police,--and would be a use less burden and expense to a cleanly and well regulated town.
